  "prompt": "Differentiate a^x up to 4 terms?",
  "response": "To differentiate the function \\( a^x \\) where \\( a \\) is a constant, we can use the chain rule and the property of exponential functions. The derivative of \\( a^x \\) is:\n\n1. First derivative:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x) = a^x \\ln(a)\n   \\]\n\n2. Second derivative:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}(a^x) = \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x \\ln(a)) = a^x (\\ln(a))^2\n   \\]\n\n3. Third derivative:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d^3}{dx^3}(a^x) = \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x (\\ln(a))^2) = a^x (\\ln(a))^3\n   \\]\n\n4. Fourth derivative:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d^4}{dx^4}(a^x) = \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x (\\ln(a))^3) = a^x (\\ln(a))^4\n   \\]\n\nPutting it all together, we have:\n\n- First derivative: \\( \\frac{d}{dx}(a^x) = a^x \\ln(a) \\)\n- Second derivative: \\( \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}(a^x) = a^x (\\ln(a))^2 \\)\n- Third derivative: \\( \\frac{d^3}{dx^3}(a^x) = a^x (\\ln(a))^3 \\)\n- Fourth derivative: \\( \\frac{d^4}{dx^4}(a^x) = a^x (\\ln(a))^4 \\)",
